inductive Subcircuit (R : Type) {X Y : Type} {A : Type} (name : String) (mod : Module R) (inputs : Type) (outputs : Type) : Prop where
  | h : (x : inputs) -> (y : outputs) -> Subcircuit.mod.eval x y → Subcircuit
```
But in `h_main`, it seems that it is `x : inputs → (y : outputs → Subcircuit mod.eval x y → _)`, which in our case means that we can choose any `y` and any proof of `mod.eval x y`, to get a `Subcircuit`. 

But in our case, when `pc.val ≥ programSize`, the `mod.eval x y` for `subcircuitWithAssertion` will be false, because it cannot find `hasAt`. 

Thus, in Lean, perhaps the way to make `h_holds s` inhabited is to use the `h_2` case for some of the subcircuits, where we return `False`.

But the `h_2` cases only exist if the subcircuit is `False`. 

Alternatively, perhaps the `h_main` can actually return `False` because it uses `Subcircuit`, but Lean doesn't check whether `mod.eval x y` can actually be fulfilled.

But perhaps in Lean, even if `mod.eval x y` cannot be fulfilled, we can still `_ => by absurd _`, because the `h_main` has to provide some proof, and maybe it can use `False.elim`. 

For example, for the first `subcircuitWithAssertion`, we can choose to make it `h_2`, which would require `¬ (HasAt ...)` to be true. 

But perhaps in Lean, when we cannot satisfy `HasAt`, then the `h_2` case is possible
